And I'm Beth

5
00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:19.000
Head over heels, butterflies in the tummy, the apple of my eye.

6
00:00:19.000 --> 00:00:25.000
In English there are many idioms to describe what it feels like to fall in love.

7
00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:28.000
I did a no-use, such a romantic nail.

8
00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:33.000
But do you know what's actually happening in our brains when we fall in love?

9
00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:38.000
Because I'm sorry to say this Neil, but it's more about brain chemistry than romance.

10
00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:48.000
Specifically hormones, chemical messengers, which the body releases into the blood to control our growth, mood, and yes, falling in love.

11
00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:51.000
Thanks for ruining my romantic ideas, Beth.

12
00:00:52.000 --> 00:01:02.000
And since my dreams are now shattered, why don't we spend the rest of this programme finding out exactly what is going on inside our bodies and brains when we fall in love?

13
00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:05.000
And of course, learn some useful new vocabulary too.

14
00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:13.000
There's no doubt that being in love has the health benefit of reducing stress, even lengthening your life.

15
00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:18.000
But the hormones which the brain releases have an immediate effect as well.

16
00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:29.000
So chemically speaking, what happens when lovers look into each other's eyes? Is it a, their body temperature increases?

17
00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:37.000
B, their heart beats harmonise, or C, the hairs stand up on the back of their neck.

18
00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:44.000
Is it all three? No, okay then. I'll guess it's B, their heart beats harmonise.

19
00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:49.000
Okay, we'll find out if that's correct at the end of the programme.

20
00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:59.000
According to Helen E. Fisher, South Help author and anthropologist at Rutgers University, there are three aspects of romantic love.

21
00:01:59.000 --> 00:02:02.000
Here's BBC ideas to explain more.

22
00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:05.000
Often loss comes first, but not always.

23
00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:08.000
For some people who are asexual, it may not happen at all.

24
00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:14.000
But for those who do experience lust, it's driven by the hormones estrogen and testosterone.

25
00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:22.000
It may feel purely carnal, but in fact, it's about the urge to mate and pass on your DNA via offspring.

26
00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:27.000
Without lust, it's fair to say, our species would not survive.

27
00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:32.000
Helen Fisher thinks the first aspect of love is purely physical.

28
00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:37.000
Lust, the strong feeling of sexual desire for someone.

29
00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:42.000
Lust is driven by the hormones estrogen in women and testosterone in men.

30
00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:48.000
A few people are asexual, meaning they don't feel sexual attraction for anyone of any gender.

31
00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:55.000
Lust is hardwired into us through our DNA, and it drives us to have children.

32
00:02:55.000 --> 00:03:01.000
Helen thinks it's fair to say that without lust, our species would not survive.

33
00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:09.000
Here she uses the phrase it's fair to say to introduce an idea she believes to be true and reasonable.

34
00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:18.000
Of course, love is not just physical. Here's BBC ideas again to introduce Helen Fisher's second aspect of love attraction.

35
00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:25.000
The second aspect of romantic love is attraction, influenced by a neurotransmitter called dopamine.

36
00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:32.000
This is a feel good substance, released in our brain that is involved in driving us towards reward.

37
00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:36.000
Do something, get a dopamine hit, feel good.

38
00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:41.000
Eventually dopamine will push us towards repeating that behavior.

39
00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:46.000
This is why intense attraction feels like an addiction to another human being.

40
00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:53.000
Some people get stuck in that loop, always chasing the dopamine-soaked excitement of a new relationship.

41
00:03:53.000 --> 00:04:02.000
This time, the hormone responsible is dopamine, a neurotransmitter that rewards our attraction to someone with pleasurable feelings.

42
00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:06.000
That's why dopamine is called a feel good substance.

43
00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:17.000
The adjective feel good can be used to describe anything causing happy and optimistic feelings about life, things like feel good films or feel good music.

44
00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:26.000
Here though, there's a downside. The dopamine hit of sexual attraction feels so good, we crave it more and more.

45
00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:33.000
Some people are always chasing the next relationship to get a new hit of pleasure and soon become stuck in a loop.

46
00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:40.000
An idea meaning they're unable to break the habit of repeating the same patterns of behavior over and over again.

47
00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:50.000
It's fascinating to see the power which hormones have over us, but if you're an old fashioned romantic, like Neil, don't despair.

48
00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:54.000
And speaking as a romantic, how about the answer to my question?

49
00:04:54.000 --> 00:05:00.000
Right, you asked me about the effect on the body when two lovers look deep into each other's eyes.

50
00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:04.000
I guess it was that their heart beats harmonise.

51
00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:13.000
The correct answer. In experiments, looking into the eyes, produced hormones causing couples' hearts to beat in time.

52
00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:22.000
Okay, let's recap the vocabulary we've learned in this program, starting with the idiom head over heels, to be completely in love with someone.

53
00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:26.000
Last is a very strong feeling of sexual desire.

54
00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:32.000
Someone who is a sexual does not feel sexual attraction towards any one of any gender.

55
00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:39.000
The phrase it's fair to say is used to introduce a statement you believe to be true and reasonable.

56
00:05:39.000 --> 00:05:45.000
The adjective feel good describes something which makes people feel happy and optimistic.

57
00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:56.000
And finally, the idiom stuck in a loop describes someone unable to break the habit of repeating the same negative patterns of behavior over and over again.

58
00:05:56.000 --> 00:06:05.000
